    {
        "content": "<p>Actually subspace topology is handled in a neat way in Mathlib. You can make the subspace into a subtype <code>Y = {x : X // P x}</code> and then the subspace topology on <code>Y</code> is the coarsest that makes the map <code>.val</code> from <code>Y</code> to <code>X</code> continuous.<br>\nSee for instance <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=continuous_subtype_val#doc\">docs#continuous_subtype_val</a></p>",
        "id": 487174374,
        "sender_full_name": "Bjørn Kjos-Hanssen",
        "timestamp": 1733813796
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Following this idea you can define open sets of S as pre images of open sets of X by the inclusion map</p>",
        "id": 487190932,
        "sender_full_name": "Etienne Marion",
        "timestamp": 1733820312
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Then thanks to the properties of preimages proving that it is a topology becomes easy</p>",
        "id": 487191121,
        "sender_full_name": "Etienne Marion",
        "timestamp": 1733820367
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have followed <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"703970\">@Etienne Marion</span>'s advice and am making progress.  Thank you.I have found a function <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/Defs/Induced.html#TopologicalSpace.induced\">TopologicalSpace.induced</a> in mathlib that is almost exactly what I need.  I am currently dissecting those proofs.<br>\nThanks to <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"347475\">@Bjørn Kjos-Hanssen ☀️</span> , too.</p>",
